summary: I resonate to Aziraphale. I get Aziraphale. Because it’s just like-- When he’s around humans, he’s on his very best behaviour....
body:
I resonate to Aziraphale. I get Aziraphale.

Because it’s just like–

When he’s around humans, he’s on his very best behaviour. He’s kind and gentle and fixes their bikes and tells them to have nice dreams and inspires them and soothes them and, and, and, gosh, isn’t he nice, really, he’s just such an angel–

And when he’s by himself he introverts as hard as possible–

And when he’s with Crowley, the one being who gets it, he just - well, after a drink or two, plausible deniability don’t you know - he just yodels:

“I had the most ghastly day, I had to smile at everyone and there were three miracles and they were all soppy nonsense, and can you imagine there were customers in my shop? actually? in? my? shop? and they wouldn’t leave and then the telephone rang twice and the questions were so stupid and then I had to go out last minute and solve someone’s crisis of faith and I just, Crowley, I’m exhausted, really, how do you suppose all the others do it? Am I being a bit over the top? You can tell me, really, be honest.”

Crowley is, with some effort, not smiling.

“Maybe you should try being a demon. Really properly being one, I mean. I think we have more fun. I know I do.”

“Oh, it’s all awful, I’m just exhausted, don’t even bother tempting me, I’m sure it would be exactly the same; pour me another, there’s a kind soul, and let’s watch the television broadcast about the ‘alien’ with the box and the scientific devices and I don’t want to say another word.”

My baby~~~

summary: I am letting my imagination go absolutely hogwild over possible Good Omens scenarios over here. Like, fallen Aziraphale? After...
body:
I am letting my imagination go absolutely hogwild over possible Good Omens scenarios over here.

Like, fallen Aziraphale?

After the Armageddon that wasn’t, his wings just start to turn black.  And he’s on the verge of a breakdown because that’s who he is.  

Then Crowley calls him “angel” and smiles at him, and Aziraphale knows everything is going to be okay.  Because he will always be Crowley’s angel and that’s the only thing that matters.

tags: i've been thinking about it all night and it made me sad
summary: I just get really sad imagining Aziraphale in that gentleman's club during Crowley's Century Nap™️ sitting in a corner, feeling...
body:
I just get really sad imagining Aziraphale in that gentleman’s club during Crowley’s Century Nap™️ sitting in a corner, feeling listless and very alone– a feeling he has never felt before and thus has no proper cure or coping mechanism for. He misses his infernal counterpart and is far too proud to realize that that is what it is. So he goes on, sulking and pining, waiting but what for? And in the midst of it all someone takes notice of him, this sad man in the corner of an otherwise joyous place filled with young men living and existing without abandon, and finally takes pity on him. He comes up to Aziraphale, this lad who is young and kind, offering up his name (let’s say, David) just as he offers him his hand to lead Azira to a part of the floor that’s usually cleared for an orchestra on busy nights but is, for now, empty. David pulls into this game a friend of his, another young lad, only a little older than Aziraphale’s rescuer, but just as wide eyed and bright, with a violin so tenderly cradled in the crook of his neck.

And they teach the sad angel how to dance. It takes long because they’re both very thorough, with David’s friend (let’s say, Jonathan) as musical accompaniment and David patiently teaching the steps, but the whole process manages to get out a little smile from Azira. Makes him forget a bit. By the end of the evening, he’s dancing like a pro, earning him a few claps from bystanders nearby, and the beaming smiles of his saviours. For a second, he isn’t so alone, isn’t so tired from the constant pulling and yearning that something inside him has for the presence that practically lives at the crook of his left elbow.

But then, David and Jonathan bid him a good night, under the cover of darkness, and leave side-by-side, Jonathan’s arm intertwined with David’s, bodies curved toward each other as easy conversation flows between them like water, and suddenly the empty void at his side left behind by Crowley pulses deep and throbs with a pain he can’t find the words to describe, much less explain.

For a night, Aziraphale forgets, but when the sun begins to rise, burning the ink black sky back into the murky grey of a tedious morning, he shuts himself up in his dreadfully empty bookshop and tries not to think of how barren his sofa looks without its usual occupant there, demanding his attention.

summary: Ghost Hunters are sent to investigate a haunted hotel with two notorious ghosts, one they call Crowley, who throws dead house...
body:
Ghost Hunters are sent to investigate a haunted hotel with two notorious ghosts, one they call Crowley, who throws dead house plants at occupants and moves all the live ones to the hotel’s library

and the other they call Zira, Zira’s the hotel’s favourite, he mostly haunts the library and is very fond of sweets, apparently if you bring a fresh baked goods in the library, you’ll feel a sudden rush of happiness.
